# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nuttx-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The Apache Software Foundation is a decentralized open source community of developers.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The software they produce is distributed under the terms of the Apache License, a permissive open-source license for free and open-source software (FOSS).
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The Apache projects are characterized by a collaborative, consensus-based development process and an open and pragmatic software license, which is to say that it allows developers, who receive the software freely, to redistribute it under non-free terms.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Each project is managed by a self-selected team of technical experts who are active contributors to the project.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The ASF is a meritocracy, with membership granted only to volunteers who have actively contributed to Apache projects.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Among the ASF's objectives are: to provide legal protection to volunteers working on Apache projects, and to prevent the "Apache" brand name from being used by other organizations without permission.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The ASF holds several Community Over Code conferences each year, highlighting Apache projects and related technology.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The history of the Apache Software Foundation is linked to the Apache HTTP Server.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Beginning in February 1993, a group of eight developers—later known as the Apache Group—started working on enhancing the NCSA HTTPd daemon, and on March 25, 1999, they formed the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Its first official meeting was held on April 13, 1999, and after a series of additional meetings to elect board members and resolve other legal matters regarding incorporation, the effective incorporation date of the Apache Software Foundation was set to June 1, 1999.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The initial "Apache Group" members of the Apache Software Foundation were: Brian Behlendorf, Ken Coar, Miguel Gonzales, Mark Cox, Lars Eilebrecht, Ralf S.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Fielding, Dean Gaudet, Ben Hyde, Jim Jagielski, Alexei Kosut, Martin Kraemer, Ben Laurie, Doug MacEachern, Aram Mirzadeh, Sameer Parekh, Cliff Skolnick, Marc Slemko, William (Bill) Stoddard, Paul Sutton, Randy Terbush and Dirk-Willem van Gulik.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Apache divides its software development activities into separate semi-autonomous areas called "top-level projects" (formally known as a "Project Management Committee" in the bylaws), some of which have a number of sub-projects.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Unlike some other organizations that host FOSS projects, before a project is hosted at Apache it has to be licensed to the ASF with a grant or contributor agreement.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] In this way, the ASF gains the necessary intellectual property rights for the development and distribution of all its projects.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The board of directors of The Apache Software Foundation (ASF) is responsible for management and oversight of the business and affairs of the corporation in accordance with the Bylaws.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] This includes management of the corporate assets (funds, intellectual property, trademarks, and support equipment), appointment of a President and corporate officers managing the core operations of the ASF, and allocation of corporate resources for the benefit of Apache projects.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] Technical decision-making authority for every Apache project is assigned to their independent project management committee; the participants in each project provide direction, not the board.
[src:nuttx-rtos/apache-software-foundation] The board is elected annually by the ASF membership.
[src:nuttx-rtos/nuttx] NuttX was initially released in 2007 under the permissive BSD license.
[src:nuttx-rtos/nuttx] In December 2019, it began incubation at the Apache Software Foundation.; its license was changed from the BSD license to the Apache License and it graduated to a top-level project in November 2022.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The **Portable Operating System Interface** (**POSIX**; IPA: /ˈpɒz.ɪks/) is a family of standards specified by the IEEE Computer Society for maintaining compatibility between operating systems.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] In order to define a level of compatibility, POSIX specifies many aspects of functionality that can be classified as application programming interface (API), command-line shell, and shell commands.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Originally derived from commonly-found Unix APIs, shells, and commands (partly because Unix was considered manufacturer-neutral), today many systems conform to the standard – including branded Unix systems, Unix-like systems, and many systems that were historically unrelated to Unix.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The standardized user command line and scripting interface were based on the UNIX System V Bourne shell.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Many user-level programs, services, and utilities (including awk, echo, ed) were also standardized, based on UNIX System V versions of them, along with required program-level services (including basic I/O: file, terminal, and network).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] POSIX also defines a standard threading library API which is supported by most modern operating systems.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The POSIX standard is developed by the Austin Group (a joint working group among the IEEE, The Open Group, and the ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22/WG 15).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] POSIX is intended to be used by both application and system developers.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The standards emerged from a project that began in 1984 building on work from related activity in the */usr/group* association.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Richard Stallman suggested the name *POSIX* to the IEEE instead of the former *IEEE-IX*.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The committee found it more easily pronounceable and memorable, and thus adopted it.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Originally, POSIX referred to IEEE Std 1003.1-1988, released in 1988.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The family of POSIX standards is formally designated as **IEEE 1003** and the ISO/IEC standard number is ISO/IEC 9945.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] POSIX originally consisted of a single document for core services but over time additional documents were published to extend and revise the specification.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Before 1997, POSIX comprised multiple documents that were published over the course of several years.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] After 1997, the Austin Group produces specifications titled Single UNIX Specification (SUS).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Over time, the group publishes versions of this specification and later POSIX is amended per some or all of a SUS version.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] A SUS version consists of a collection of volumes – each for a grouping of required behavior – plus other information (outside of a volume).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Each volume is assigned an issue number that is the same for each volume of a version, but is not the same value as the version.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] For example, SUS version 3 (SUSv3) includes volumes labeled issue 6.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] IEEE Std 1003.1-2004 modifies POSIX.1-2001 via two minor updates or errata referred to as technical corrigenda documents.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Similar to its predecessor, POSIX.1-2008 (*IEEE Std 1003.1-2008*, 2016 Edition) consists of most of the normative material of SUSv4 (issue 7 of volumes *Base Definitions*, *System Interfaces and Headers*, *Commands and Utilities*).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] SUSv4 also includes rationale information that largely applies to POSIX although not included per se.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] As of POSIX 2024, the standard is aligned with the C17 language standard.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] POSIX mandates 512-byte default block sizes for the df and du utilities, reflecting the typical size of blocks on disks.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] When Richard Stallman and the GNU team were implementing POSIX for the GNU operating system, they objected to this on the grounds that most people think in terms of 1024 byte (or 1 KiB) blocks.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The environment variable POSIX_ME_HARDER was introduced to allow the user to force the standards-compliant behaviour.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The variable name was later changed to POSIXLY_CORRECT.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] As of 2025, this variable is also used for a number of other behaviour quirks.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] An operating system can be classified depending upon the degree of conformance with a POSIX standard.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Current versions of the following operating systems have been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests and their certification has not expired and the operating system has not been discontinued.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Some versions of the following operating systems had been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The certification has expired and some of the operating systems have been discontinued.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The following operating systems are not certified as POSIX conformant, but they conform in large part to the standard by implementing POSIX support via a compatibility feature (usually translation libraries, or a layer atop the kernel).
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Some technologies allow an operating system to enjoy a level of conformance to POSIX even though the operating system itself has little or no conformance.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] Although Windows does not conform to POSIX, the following technologies provide a level of compliance.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] A lightweight implementation that has POSIX-compatible header files that map POSIX APIs to call their Windows API counterparts.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] An optional Windows subsystem included in Windows NT-based operating systems up to Windows 2000.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] A compatibility layer for running Linux binary executables natively on Windows 10 and 11 using a Linux image such as Ubuntu, Debian, or OpenSUSE among others, acting as an upgrade and replacement for Windows Services for UNIX.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] The first distribution available was Ubuntu.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] From AT&T Research implements a POSIX layer on top of the Win32 APIs.
[src:nuttx-rtos/posix] although the support remains largely incomplete and not fully interoperable with POSIX-compliant implementations.
[src:nuttx-rtos/px4-autopilot] The **PX4 autopilot** is an open-source system for autonomous aircraft.
[src:nuttx-rtos/px4-autopilot] PX4 is capable of integrating with other autopilot software, such as the QGroundControl ground control station software, via the MAVLink protocol (though they provide limited px4 -> Unity documentation).
[src:nuttx-rtos/px4-autopilot] PX4 is open-source and available under a BSD-3-Clause license.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:nuttx-rtos/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] A **Unix-like** operating system (sometimes referred to as a **UN*X,** ***nix** or ***NIX**) is one that behaves in a manner similar to a Unix system, although not necessarily conforming to or being certified to any version of the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] A Unix-like application is one that behaves like the corresponding Unix command or shell.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Although there are general philosophies for Unix design, there is no technical standard defining the term, and opinions can differ about the degree to which a particular operating system or application is Unix-like.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Some well-known examples of Unix-like operating systems include Linux, FreeBSD and OpenBSD.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] These systems are often used on servers as well as on personal computers and other devices.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Many popular applications, such as the Apache web server and the Bash shell, are also designed to be used on Unix-like systems.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] The Open Group owns the UNIX trademark and administers the Single UNIX Specification, with the "UNIX" name being used as a certification mark.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] They do not approve of the construction "Unix-like" and consider it a misuse of their trademark.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Their guidelines require "UNIX" to be presented in uppercase or otherwise distinguished from the surrounding text, strongly encourage using it as a branding adjective for a generic word such as "system", and discourage its use in hyphenated phrases.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Other parties frequently treat "Unix" as a genericized trademark.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Some add a wildcard character to the name to make an abbreviation like "Un*x" or "*nix", since Unix-like systems often have Unix-like names such as AIX, A/UX, HP-UX, IRIX, Linux, Minix, Ultrix, Xenix, and XNU.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] These patterns do not literally match many system names, but are still generally recognized to refer to any UNIX system, descendant, or work-alike, even those with completely dissimilar names such as Darwin/macOS, illumos/Solaris or FreeBSD.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Gray sued to dispute the status of UNIX as a trademark, claiming Novell did not lawfully own the trademark when they transferred it to X/Open (pointing to The SCO Group's statements which had, by then, already been deemed invalid by a court).
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] He lost his case, and lost again on appeal, with the court upholding the trademark and its ownership.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] "Unix-like" systems started to appear in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Many proprietary versions, such as Idris (1978), UNOS (1982), Coherent (1983), and UniFlex (1985), aimed to provide businesses with the functionality available to academic users of UNIX.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] When AT&T allowed relatively inexpensive commercial binary sublicensing of UNIX in 1979, a variety of proprietary systems were developed based on it, including AIX, HP-UX, IRIX, SunOS, Tru64, Ultrix, and Xenix.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] These largely displaced the proprietary clones.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Growing incompatibility among these systems led to the creation of interoperability standards, including POSIX and the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Various free, low-cost, and unrestricted substitutes for UNIX emerged in the 1980s and 1990s, including 4.4BSD, Linux, and Minix.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Some of these have in turn been the basis for commercial "Unix-like" systems, such as BSD/OS and macOS.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Several versions of (Mac) OS X/macOS running on Intel-based and Apple silicon-based Mac computers have been certified under the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] The BSD variants are descendants of UNIX developed by the University of California at Berkeley, with UNIX source code from Bell Labs.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] However, the BSD code base has evolved since then, replacing all the AT&T code.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Since the BSD variants are not certified as compliant with the Single UNIX Specification, they are referred to as "UNIX-like" rather than "UNIX".
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Those systems with a historical connection to the AT&T codebase.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Most commercial UNIX systems fall into this category.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] So do the BSD systems, which are descendants of work done at the University of California, Berkeley in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Some of these systems have no original AT&T code but can still trace their ancestry to AT&T designs.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Trademark, or branded, UNIX systems‍—‌largely commercial in nature‍—‌have been determined by the Open Group to meet the Single UNIX Specification and are allowed to carry the UNIX name.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Most such systems are commercial derivatives of the System V code base in one form or another, although Apple macOS 10.5 and later is a BSD variant that has been certified, and EulerOS and Inspur K-UX are Linux distributions that have been certified.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] A few other systems (such as IBM z/OS) earned the trademark through a POSIX compatibility layer and are not otherwise inherently Unix systems.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Many ancient UNIX systems no longer meet this definition.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Most free/open-source implementations of the UNIX design, whether genetic UNIX or not, fall into the restricted definition of this third category due to the expense of obtaining Open Group certification, which costs thousands of dollars.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Dennis Ritchie, one of the original creators of Unix, mentioned Linux as one of the healthiest of the direct Unix derivatives due to its strong adherence to Unix principles.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Around 2001 Linux was given the opportunity to get a certification including free help from the POSIX chair Andrew Josey for the symbolic price of one dollar.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] There have been some activities to make Linux POSIX-compliant, with Josey having prepared a list of differences between the POSIX standard and the Linux Standard Base specification, but in August 2005 this project was shut down because of lack of interest at the LSB work group.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] As per § Trademark UNIX, some Linux distributions have been certified.
[src:nuttx-rtos/unix-like] Some non-Unix-like operating systems provide a Unix-like compatibility layer, with varying degrees of Unix-like functionality.
